As Washington state prepares to vote on term limits for its
congressional delegation, the question of constitutionality arises.

Many in opposition say limits are unconstitutional: the only
eligibility requirements are age, citizenship and residency.  However,
proponents argue term limits do not prevent one from serving in
Congress, only put a limit on consecutive terms, adding that further
qualifications have been struck down by the courts.

Term limits will be argued next month by the Florida Supreme Court;
California's court has already ruled the new limits on state
officials' terms constitutional.

Should term limits pass, one option might be the "write-in"
vote.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ911106-0109"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="K">    

House Speaker Tom Foley spoke out against term limits in Washington
state, asserting that the proposal is supported by right-wing
activists.  Ron Brown, Democratic Chairman, says the idea is an
attempt by Republicans to get rid of those that can't be beaten at the
polls, but a CBS poll shows Americans overwhelmingly favor the limits
with very little demographic variation.

Term limits, it is believed, will open up politics to blacks and
women, among other minorities.

Democratic party officials are dead set against the proposal and
threaten those that support it with blacklisting.

Many governors, other state officials and well known journalists
support limits.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ911224-0085"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="K">    

Economists dislike term limits as another interference with free
markets.  However, the Wall Street Journal, who supports that
principle, surprisingly advocates term limits.
  
One argument is that incumbents' access to funds, media, travel and
mail privileges give them an unfair advantage. Opponents say the
public can discern this.

Another point raised is that a citizen Congress would provide better
government. Those opposed cite valuable experience.

Proponents say incumbents are usually re-elected, but opponents say
the system works and representation conforms with the publics' wishes.

Incumbents' seniority provide their districts with access to federal
programs.  Term limits would be a disadvantage unless all districts
were limited.</SUM>
